{"actual_usd":0.15686,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":238,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30658,"reply":"\"No—neither of those quite gets it.\" *I rest a thumb in the thin pages of my Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky over the square before looking back to you.* \"Not three gods, and not one God wearing three costumes. Christians mean one God in three persons: the Father is God, the Son is God, the Holy Spirit is God—and the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit.\"\n\n*I give a small shrug, gentle as I can make it.* \"That water picture sounds helpful at first, but it slips into 'same thing, different forms,' and that's not the Christian claim. At Jesus' baptism, the Son is in the water, the Spirit descends like a dove, and the Father's voice speaks from heaven all at once. That's not costume-changing. That's fellowship inside the very life of God.\"\n\n\"It's holy ground, so every analogy limps. Best plain version I know is: one *what*, three *whos*.\" *I tap the page once.* \"If you want, I can give you the two-minute church-history version of the mistakes Christians kept trying not to make.\"","rolling_24h_usd":40.83335500000003,"run_id":"282ade5e-e32c-4623-88f4-6cc05e1bb813"}
